<title>USA: Glickman - would be mistake to alter Freedom-to-Farm.</title>
<headline>Glickman - would be mistake to alter Freedom-to-Farm.</headline>
<dateline>WASHINGTON 1996-11-07</dateline>
<text>
<p>U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said Thursday that it would be a mistake to alter the &quot;Freedom to Farm&quot; law, and renewed a warning to Europe that unfair grain sales would prompt U.S. retaliation.</p>
<p>During a luncheon speech, Glickman said this week's congressional elections, in which Republicans retained control of both chambers, reduced prospects for amending U.S. farm policy.  </p>
<p>Glickman said USDA was &quot;watching very closely&quot; grain export subsidies being offered by the European Union.</p>
<p>&quot;We won't let unfair activities on their part ... go without reciprocal action,&quot; he said.</p>
<p>USDA officials repeatedly have warned the EU against reigniting an export subsidy war following a bumper grain harvest in Europe.</p>
